{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc68a7ff-33f4-43d4-8f6f-051d9bd194d4","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .dmp file. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so here's what you can do:\n\n### Analyze with `dotnet-dump`\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside the interactive session, useful commands:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` | Print last exception |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary |\n| `setthread <id>` then `clrstack` | Inspect a specific thread |\n\n### Quick workflow\n1. Run `pe` first — it often shows the unhandled exception that caused the crash.\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find threads with exceptions.\n3. Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect each.\n\n### Alternatives\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` directly for a richer UI experience.\n- **lldb + SOS** — on Linux: `lldb --core your-file.dmp` then `loadsos` and use the same SOS commands.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1ab3bf9b-9a57-4670-b922-dcd9732df1a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for configuring and collecting crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"6083:32FC8B:324FAB:40D8D8:69FFE576"},"id":"957bd71c-6c25-40ea-addc-95f8a6d3fde9","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:55:16.258Z",